IAR's Dlib has some problems with unbuffered stream, however I found a workaround. setvbuf with these params generate a buffer with size 1. 
-        _file->_Mode = (unsigned short)(_file->_Mode & ~ 0x1000);/\* Unset read mode */
  Is to remove read mode from _file after read because writes will otherwise be blocked.
-        _file->_Rend = _file->_Wend;
-        _file->_Next = _file->_Wend;
  If this is not set the last char from fgets will be rewritten next time (saved in buffer). So for instance if you send a \n to end a string sequence it would be a double new line. The other new line would be written as start  of the next string.

Attaching _Serial::TxIrq_ callbacks on the LPC1549 appears to disable the USB peripheral, as is evidenced by the following code:

``` C++
#include "mbed.h"
#include "USBHID.h"

USBHID hid(8, 8, 0x1234, 0x0006, 0x0001, false);
Serial pc(USBTX, USBRX);
DigitalOut led1(LED1);
DigitalOut led2(LED2);
HID_REPORT report;

void onTxIrq()
{
    led2 = !led2;
}

int main(void)
{
    //Attach a serial Tx callback (breaks USBDevice!)
    pc.attach(onTxIrq, Serial::TxIrq);

    //Connect to the host (doesn't work!)
    hid.connect(false);

    while (1) {
        //Try to read a report
        if(hid.readNB(&report)) {
            led1 = !led1;
        }
    }
}
```

After calling _pc.attach(onTxIrq, Serial::TxIrq)_, the device will no longer connect to the host. However, if _pc.attach(onTxIrq, Serial::TxIrq)_ is removed, or changed to a _Serial::RxIrq_ type, connecting to the host works fine.

